WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:07.739
In the early 30s,

00:00.031 --> 00:07.739
you couldn't find anybody in Texas except a 
Democrat. My grandfather, boy, he'd read the

00:08.760 --> 00:17.770
paper every day and anything that was counted as a 
Democratic party. Of course, you couldn't get

00:17.790 --> 00:22.795
elected in the South, but particularly Texas. And 
so they may have been Republican philosophy

00:22.815 --> 00:27.540
somewhere, but... But as you just mentioned, very 
few people knew anything about Republicans. You

00:33.270 --> 00:34.993
had to go back to Hoover. And everybody said he was 
responsible for depression, which, of course, he

00:35.013 --> 00:38.397
wasn't. But he happened to be the guy that gets 
blamed for it.

00:47.390 --> 00:56.363
So no, to answer your question, I guess a political 
philosophy never did enter my mind. as I was

00:57.642 --> 01:02.287
growing up.

01:02.307 --> 01:09.214
And I don't know anybody that I associated with 
very strongly because nobody ever talked about

01:02.307 --> 01:09.214
anything except Democrats. Now, over the years, 
would you consider yourself a conservative,

01:09.234 --> 01:15.100
moderate, or a liberal? And what parties did you 
support over the years?

01:24.794 --> 01:28.699
I'm ashamed to say this, but until I retired, I 
never did vote. And the reason why it makes it very

01:30.341 --> 01:35.729
difficult for the military, because you're gone, 
you've got to send in an absentee vote. And up until

01:36.129 --> 01:39.133
a few years ago, you had to pay your poll tax. And I 
wanted to go pay poll tax and back to the, which I was

01:40.335 --> 01:47.685
against poll tax. We know what the poll tax was for. 
It keeps the blacks away. And poor white kind of

01:54.578 --> 02:05.570
eliminated a whole element of society.

02:08.032 --> 02:22.948
But to answer your question, I think I've always 
been more on the conservative side

02:08.032 --> 02:22.948
in political philosophy.

02:23.772 --> 02:28.317
Of course, if I had voted back in those days, I would 
have voted for Roosevelt, no question in my mind.

02:31.180 --> 02:32.782
What about more recent America?

02:38.769 --> 02:42.333
I guess I tend to be more conservative. I vote 
Republican now. I voted in every election since I

02:43.815 --> 02:48.480
retired, local and then I'm active now in the 
community. And are you a member of the Republican

02:53.200 --> 02:57.105
Party? Yeah. But back in those days in the 
military, once again, there are two reasons for

02:59.428 --> 03:03.773
that. That's pretty typical. A lot of officers 
didn't vote. Well, one reason is that nobody has

03:07.016 --> 03:17.809
ever appealed to the military to... We've never 
been involved with politics. And I'm horrified

03:18.869 --> 03:22.333
when somebody tries to tie us to politics. For 
example, they wanted to fire the chairman of the

03:22.994 --> 03:32.023
Joint Chiefs, see, because he supported a program 
of Carter. Well, that would be a hell of a note if we

03:32.985 --> 03:47.020
ever got to a point that every time you change 
presidents, you purge your military and get rid of

03:32.985 --> 03:47.020
all the leaders and bring in somebody else, you'll 
end up being like a banana republic. And that was a

03:47.978 --> 03:49.419
very dangerous thing. But fortunately, Reagan, 
an advisor, said, absolutely not. He will

03:55.526 --> 03:58.048
continue and fulfill his term. And he's not going 
to be replaced because he went along with

03:59.429 --> 04:03.453
reluctantly. And he's an Air Force officer. 
Reluctantly was the B-1.

04:10.961 --> 04:16.146
You can't have military to lead a revolt against 
their, I don't mean a physical revolt, media

04:17.003 --> 04:22.810
revolt against the president if you disagree with 
the decision he's made. All you got to do is resign

04:23.771 --> 04:27.275
if that's the way you feel. And most of them, and I 
subscribe to this, they can do more good for all of

04:28.216 --> 04:39.328
the principles that they stand for to stay rather 
than to run. That would be a difficult situation

04:39.368 --> 04:44.614
too if every time the president made a decision 
that the leaders and the military disliked, they

04:44.813 --> 04:47.177
would all resign.

04:50.903 --> 04:53.987
Because a professional soldier to me is the 
nation. Just like West Point, duty, honor, and

04:54.308 --> 04:56.632
country. And it's not political persuasion. And 
so from that standpoint, I don't think the

04:59.296 --> 05:04.164
military should get involved in politics. Now 
voting, of course, is a different thing. But even

05:05.886 --> 05:12.677
then, I don't think we should get out a letter to 
each other and say, now let's all get together. and

05:14.480 --> 05:17.423
vote Republican or Democrat or something like 
that. And you work with your troops, you know, you

05:17.503 --> 05:20.326
tell them. Yeah, absolutely. So the military 
ought to stay completely away from politics, even

05:22.448 --> 05:33.178
if it means that you're not taking advantage of 
your vote. The other thing is, I don't think that

05:33.198 --> 05:42.327
somebody stationed in Germany, which I spent some 
time there in other parts of the world, should have

05:44.332 --> 05:47.136
an influence on a local election. They're not 
there. They don't know the people. So they'd have

05:49.820 --> 05:51.242
to vote either. Somebody said, hey, would you 
please submit your application and vote for

05:51.663 --> 05:56.489
so-and-so? And they don't even know the issues. 
That's right. You don't even know the person. It'd

05:59.834 --> 06:02.939
be better if you just stayed out and let the people 
who are not. We have a situation here in Austin

06:04.701 --> 06:12.853
that's kind of, well, we who live here, it's kind of 
touchy. The university students, they vote on a

06:13.171 --> 06:16.835
