life, see the camp and so forth. So when they 
graduate, then when they graduate, they have a

27:08.148 --> 27:09.469
considerably more experienced.

27:14.094 --> 27:28.888
Well, that would have put A&M superior to the other 
ROTC programs, except when you consider the

27:14.094 --> 27:28.888
Citadel, VMI, and API. No, the school up in

27:28.908 --> 27:33.953
Massachusetts.

27:38.152 --> 27:47.241
But BMI and the Citadel, they are very similar to 
West Point in that they devote much more time. But

27:49.083 --> 27:56.350
A&M in those days would,

27:49.083 --> 27:56.350
I'd say, be right up there. Of course, I'm biased. 
I'd put A&M next to the military academy. But those

28:00.114 --> 28:06.100
other schools are very fine. From a military 
standpoint. But in general, from military

28:07.770 --> 28:13.095
training, you put West Point on number one tops. 
Yeah.

28:19.802 --> 28:21.864
Because they're limited 24 hours a day. Yeah. OK. 
See, every class. Of course, it's impossible now.

28:27.570 --> 28:28.791
You're not comparing. You can't compare the Corps 
cadets.

28:35.442 --> 28:41.248
At A&M now, of course, I don't know how they operate 
now with West Point. Because I say, there is 24

28:41.268 --> 28:43.230
hours a day.

28:47.014 --> 28:58.086
Even their academic

28:47.014 --> 28:58.086
is military controlled discipline type thing, 
even though they have professors, of course, that

28:47.014 --> 28:58.086
are highly qualified. And they have permanent 
professors, which means that they no longer, they

29:03.978 --> 29:05.520
won't actually do anything like that. Most of 
them, of course, have PhDs in their particular

29:06.642 --> 29:10.587
specialty.

29:15.133 --> 29:18.618
But now it's different. In many cases, a graduate 
of ROTC now can run out of school now. We're talking

29:24.927 --> 29:30.975
about right after graduation.

29:30.995 --> 29:33.799
Because of the school system that you graduate 
from A&M, Then you go to, well, first you go to,

29:34.589 --> 29:41.619
their summer camp now is much different than the 
summer camp we had. It was more intense.

29:45.845 --> 29:48.468
So they got training very similar. Now I'm going to 
appear to contradict myself. People think of West

29:51.733 --> 29:55.738
Point as being just a military. But they spend so 
much of their time on academics, when you add it all

29:56.920 --> 30:02.908
up together now, there isn't a great deal of 
difference. Both of them intend to get their

30:03.563 --> 30:07.268
education after they graduate. In other words, 
you have basic training as a lieutenant, and

30:08.590 --> 30:11.614
you're qualified then. But you really got to 
specialize. It didn't fare. And I know that, but we

30:14.618 --> 30:16.521
did at West Point. These kids graduated, and we 
sent them to Korea while I was up there. And I went to

30:20.666 --> 30:24.091
Korea and interviewed all of these youngsters. 
And it wasn't fair to put them out and throw them

30:24.111 --> 30:29.318
right into combat, because they had intended for 
them to go to school, to Benning, to engineer

30:30.007 --> 30:39.917
school, wherever it is, and really develop the 
skill and the knowledge that you'd expect of a

30:30.007 --> 30:39.917
second lieutenant. And they had a heavy caliber. 
It wasn't because of lack of knowledge that they

30:43.041 --> 30:47.546
had caliber, indirectly it was. It's because they 
were going to prove that they were graduating

30:48.046 --> 30:53.472
military academy as second lieutenant. And so 
they were out leading when they shouldn't be out

30:54.493 --> 30:58.037
there. Yeah, right. They were sacrificed. They 
had heavy cases.

31:06.557 --> 31:11.103
Let's talk about your academic career at A&M. You 
were in dairy husbandry. Did you like the

31:13.245 --> 31:14.687
curriculum? Did you enjoy the courses?

31:18.652 --> 31:19.413
I had no idea. When I graduated from high school 
that I'd be involved in things like that. But,

31:23.758 --> 31:25.140
yeah, I enjoyed it. And see, in dairy husbandry, 
you've got production and manufacturing. And I

31:30.248 --> 31:32.850
was in the manufacturing part. And so I was doing 
what, you know, in the creamer there. Sure. That

31:36.994 --> 31:37.874
was helping you. And of course, you know, your 
basic course, you take chemistry and biology and

31:38.855 --> 31:46.102
English and history, you know, a whole range of 
things. So it didn't just down to the old dairy

31:46.122 --> 31:48.664
farm. Sure. Were there professors there that had a 
particular influence on you? Right. Jefferson

31:54.869 --> 31:55.650
did. He took the time, he interviewed, talked to 
us. In fact, he wanted to keep up with each student,

32:01.046 --> 32:11.696
so he had a plan where he called Jen every once in a 
while. They'd just say, well, how you doing? Are

32:14.199 --> 32:15.580
you enjoying your work?

32:19.023 --> 32:20.905
And he'd come in business there in Greenwood.

32:24.369 --> 32:25.890
Brilliant individual. He's from the Middle West, 
I think. Minnesota, I think, is where he came from.

32:32.559 --> 32:41.431
When you finished your education, did you ever 
give any thought to going into dairy husbandry, or

32:32.559 --> 32:41.431
did you want to go right into the military? Well, if 
I hadn't gone to the military, yeah. So that was

32:45.296 --> 32:46.818
your second choice then? Yeah. In fact, I even 
thought at one time that I might probably become a

32:48.420 --> 32:55.810
veterinarian. because I hadn't taken the 
courses. Of course, I had to go take quite a few

32:58.917 --> 33:11.731
more, but it wouldn't have been much difficult 
before that.

33:13.273 --> 33:26.387
In fact, I had planned, if I had not gotten my 
regular commission in World War II, I probably

33:13.273 --> 33:26.387
would have gone back to A&M to become a 
veterinarian. I would like very much to stay in

33:26.620 --> 33:34.609
Terry Hudson, particularly the manufacturing 
part of it. And I offered a job after I graduated in

33:34.629 --> 33:39.234
San Antonio. In fact, I went for an interview.

33:45.401 --> 33:48.985
But then I had applied for Thomason Act. I don't 
know if you ever heard of Thomason Act. Sure have.

33:52.589 --> 33:54.872
The Army was understaffed of officers. And West 
Point wasn't producing sufficient. So they had a

33:58.703 --> 34:03.750
shortage of officers, acute shortage. So this 
representative named Thomason had a bill passed

34:03.770 --> 34:24.859
that would call into service 1,000 officers,

34:03.770 --> 34:24.859
ROTC graduates, for one year

34:03.770 --> 34:24.859
competitive tour of duty, which out of that 50 
would be selected for a regular commission. So

34:30.637 --> 34:42.234
just when I was being interviewed, my name was 
approved to attend

34:30.637 --> 34:42.234
or to go for a year's active duty. Of course, that's 
what I wanted. So I went to Fort Sam Houston in the

34:44.818 --> 34:47.822
second division.

34:53.390 --> 34:55.133
And how long did you stay at Fort Sam? One year. And 
tell me about the training. This is 1938. Tell me

35:00.941 --> 35:06.085
about the training.

35:06.105 --> 35:10.409
Well, I would consider now on-the-job training. I 
had a company commander named Dansby, and so he

35:11.811 --> 35:25.423
took me under his wing to teach me about

35:11.811 --> 35:25.423
really how to be a company commander, being a 
company officer. And I was the only other officer

35:26.686 --> 35:28.429
they had. Unfortunately, I had Sergeant Bieber,

35:29.370 --> 35:38.805
a German immigrant that had been in the army. He got 
into the army when he was real young, in the US Army.

35:44.574 --> 35:45.795
And he got interested in me. So he taught me. Now we 
send them to service school to go through all of

35:49.481 --> 35:53.267
this. This was only job training. And that's what 
the purpose of the year. And then later on, we had

35:56.674 --> 36:00.900
organized formal school training. So obviously, 
I became the mess officer, the supply officer, the

36:00.920 --> 36:16.201
training officer, administrative officer,

36:00.920 --> 36:16.201
and any other odd job. Like we had the inventory of 
the and the commissary. So that only happened once

36:21.028 --> 36:22.410
a month. We also had to perform as officers of the 
day.

36:29.542 --> 36:32.084
And the other was officer of the guard, officer of 
the guard. He went down to the stockade, you know,

36:32.144 --> 36:38.590
and inspected the prisoners out working. So it was 
a full-time job. Now, each of the sergeants

36:41.373 --> 36:47.319
teaches, the supply sergeant would teach you all 
about supply and the book and so forth. Same thing

36:47.359 --> 36:50.642
with the mess officer.

36:55.077 --> 37:03.385
One anecdote that I think is, that I would know 
better today, of course, but being young and want

36:55.077 --> 37:03.385
to impress my company commander. And knowing your 
first day of duty, the importance to make a

37:05.447 --> 37:10.912
faithful impression. So I had my boots all shined, 
spurs, and I was ready. So I went walking in the C

37:17.698 --> 37:21.962
Company, 9th Infantry. The medical people are 
taking all that over now. And so I walked in fresh

37:26.212 --> 37:34.342
out of A&M as a second lieutenant. And when I walked 
in, I would have yelled, . Boy, I came to attention.

37:41.851 --> 37:44.574
Used to responding. And then when I discovered 
that he was calling attention for me, the second

37:44.594 --> 37:51.122
lieutenant walked in. And he was the orderly. Orly 
was outside the company commandant's door. So

37:55.816 --> 38:02.486
then when I felt that's what had happened and 
realized it, I started to step off. And my spurs,

38:02.506 --> 38:04.790
they will hang together. They hook together. I 
tried getting those unhooked. Of course, I was

38:09.256 --> 38:10.037
embarrassed. And you could see that Orly, looking 
at the tension, but he's kind of smirk on his face

38:10.057 --> 38:16.587
like, oh, it's this lieutenant. So I walked in, and 
Captain Danley saluted Lieutenant Andrews and

38:17.191 --> 38:22.456
reported the duty. He said, oh, I'm glad to see you. 
I'm looking forward to it. I've got all this work

38:25.538 --> 38:29.021
I've got to get done. And by the way, he says, we're 
getting ready to have a parade. And I want you to

38:34.486 --> 38:36.868
take the company, because I'm busy here. I said, 
yes, sir. He said, well, you better move on out,

38:40.872 --> 38:43.174
because they're getting ready. And so Sergeant 
Beaver came up to me, and he said, I said,

38:47.448 --> 38:53.095
Lieutenant, do you know anything about mass 
formation? No, never heard of it. He said, well,

38:55.157 --> 39:04.408
this is a test division for the new triangular 
organization, and we're drilling today on mass

38:55.157 --> 39:04.408
formation. That's where the parade was. I said, 
no, I know all about right by squad, squad to right,

39:07.732 --> 39:15.261
and you know all of that stuff, which we'd been 
doing at A&M and everywhere else in the Army except

39:07.732 --> 39:15.261
for St. Lucie. He said, well, I'll tell you what 
I'll do, Lieutenant. Instead of, you know, when

39:19.179 --> 39:24.326
you follow them, you just post and the sergeant 
goes around the back. He said, I'll stay right

39:25.928 --> 39:29.432
behind you. And he said, I'll give you every 
command that you need to do. And I said, okay.

39:37.923 --> 39:40.827
Knowing what I know now, rather than, you know, 
gosh, you could have a, tragedy out there, you

39:41.330 --> 39:44.113
know, here you've got people lined up. It's an 
entire division parade, you know, and I'm taking

39:44.173 --> 39:49.358
up the company, supposed to be the final of the 
battalion. But I didn't. I said, yeah, okay,

39:52.080 --> 39:53.902
Sergeant, thank you very much. So we went out and he 
said, come to Mass Right. Well, I said, come to Mass

39:57.185 --> 39:59.147
Right. You know, they all reacted. And he carried 
me around and gave me, of course, all I had to do was

40:00.108 --> 40:08.956
know, I knew all about grieving, you know, what to 
do and all that stuff. And we carried it all the way

40:08.976 --> 40:09.717
around. passed the review and came on back to the 
company and dismissed him. And the old sergeant

40:15.033 --> 40:17.556
said, Lieutenant, you did real well. And

40:18.077 --> 40:24.465
I said, thank you, boy, I'm really indebted to you. 
And the old Danvy committed me. He said, Sergeant

40:28.370 --> 40:30.893
Beaver tells me you did a good job. That was great. 
And I never did tell him that I didn't know anything

40:33.116 --> 40:37.541
about that. I don't know. He may not realize, I 
don't know, but I'd never send a lieutenant out

40:39.245 --> 40:43.530
like that. Boy, you can really mess up here and 
embarrass me.

40:50.619 --> 40:51.680
You want to go eat now? Sure,

40:51.700 --> 40:58.088
I can go eat. OK, we were talking about life at Fort 
Sam Houston. Yeah.

41:05.384 --> 41:14.776
After your year was over there, of course, it was 
questionable if you were going to give a regular,

41:05.384 --> 41:14.776
if you would receive a regular Army commission. Is 
that not right? And tell me how that transpired,

41:16.098 --> 41:19.142
how you received it. Well, as I said, the second 
part of the year, I had to get on the job training,

41:19.262 --> 41:31.999
which the sergeants taught us a lot, which you have 
to rely very heavily, all through the military on

41:19.262 --> 41:31.999
the sergeants. Then we had organized classes 
where we went to school and stayed. Those were just

41:38.079 --> 41:44.105
map reading, something such as that, weapon 
training. And then at the end, we were given a test.

41:47.508 --> 41:55.136
And at Fort Sam Houston, we had about 20 competing. 
And only one got a regular commission, which I

41:55.156 --> 42:01.142
wasn't that one. But he was an Aggie, and it was a

42:02.135 --> 42:20.115
name comes to mind is Cersei Bracewell, but I don't 
think that was the one. He was an artilleryman, I

42:20.135 --> 42:21.797
remember.

42:24.840 --> 42:31.247
So then after the year was over, of course, we had to 
wait to see whether or not And that didn't receive

42:32.189 --> 42:35.132
work. We found out later on it only once. So I had a 
month's leave. So I hitchhiked by air. People

42:46.065 --> 42:49.528
laugh when I say that, because how do you hitchhike 
by air? But went out to the military field to go to

42:50.590 --> 43:01.622
operations and ask for their plane going to the 
west coast. Finally, I got a ride out to the West

43:01.855 --> 43:03.917
Coast. San Francisco, went to the San Francisco 
World's Fair, which was one of the great

43:04.358 --> 43:11.485
attractions. Sally ran in the news range. And then 
hitchhiked, went out to one of the local fields,

43:15.789 --> 43:26.040
and hitchhiked back to Dallas. And this would be a 
great historical occurrence. It was a nonstop

43:30.544 --> 43:39.453
flight in a bomber from California to Dallas. It 
was overnight. We left about dark and got to Dallas

43:41.174 --> 43:47.120
early in the morning.

43:47.140 --> 43:50.784
It was a predecessor to the B-17 . Of course, it was a 
smaller plane, the B-17. Then I hitchhiked from

43:56.378 --> 44:05.107
Dallas, from Hensley Field to New York, and went to 
the New York World's Fair. This is 1939. Yeah, the

44:05.988 --> 44:17.881
big attraction there was Billy Rose and Aqua, I 
guess it was, with Esther Williams. Martin Downey

44:19.102 --> 44:20.844
was the singer. And then returned back to Texas.

44:27.091 --> 44:33.440
And went to work for Nettie Cade, the Ford place in 
Caldwell. But knowing that the way things were

44:35.323 --> 44:39.889
going, it looked like there'd be war pretty soon. 
But in the meantime, back to the 143rd Infantry,

44:41.532 --> 44:54.490
the Texas National Guard again, they were 
recruiting lieutenants. So I was contacted. and

44:56.605 --> 45:01.151
asked if I wanted to be a second lieutenant in the 
National Guard. And I said yes, so I transferred in

45:02.793 --> 45:06.718
the National Guard, second lieutenant. And soon 
thereafter, the National Guard was mobilized.

45:14.789 --> 45:15.650
And I think... In 1940. Yeah, in October 1940, May 
1st, November 1940. And that was the beginning

45:21.818 --> 45:25.903
of... Continuous active duty until retirement. 
And what happened to your status, your

45:30.499 --> 45:35.066
commission? Were you then commissioned as a 
reserve officer or as an active officer? You mean

45:41.996 --> 45:44.340
during World War II? Yeah. See, you were with the 
National Guard, which is usually a reserve army

45:44.600 --> 45:51.010
officer. Yeah. When did you get a regular 
commission? I was a reserve officer, a National

45:58.257 --> 46:05.865
Guard officer, which you say is the same, through 
World War II. And then they had the integration

46:08.467 --> 46:12.972
program.

46:15.514 --> 46:18.918
I was interested in that, of course. And I was 
stationed at Fort Benning. Infantry School as an

46:20.744 --> 46:24.429
instructor after World War II. And they started 
sending out telegrams, you know, to the people.

46:30.197 --> 46:36.587
And I didn't think I'd made it because I was one of 
the last ones to get it, even though my name started

46:30.197 --> 46:36.587
with A. Apparently they broke up the whole roster 
and those that sent that part of it, it was

46:36.627 --> 46:44.297
dispatched later than the others.

46:47.782 --> 46:48.203
And that was...

